To simulate the outlier bias we follow two strategies as follows:
OPBM𝑅𝑒𝑎𝑙. We use the propensities estimated by OPBM (see Sec-
tion 4) on our proprietary dataset. From all the abnormal rankings in
our dataset, 64% contain only one outlier. Since improving ranking
for more than half of queries can lead to significant improvement in
real-world scenarios, we first address this majority case. Therefore,
with this model, we focus on rankings with one outlier. Thus, the
output of OPBM is at most a 𝐾× 𝐾matrix, corresponding to all
combinations of rank and outlier position, where 𝐾= 10 in our
experiments. We use this matrix to approximate 𝑃(𝐸= 1 | 𝑘,𝑜).
OPBMG . Here, we assume that an outlier’s effect on the user clicks
follows a Gaussian distribution, centered at the outlier’s position.
Therefore, for each 𝑘, we compute the linear interpolation of outlier

